<subsection xml:id="subsec-Constructing-triangles">
    <title>Constructing triangles</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-Definition-of-triangle">
            <statement>
                <p>
                A triangle is a basic shape with three sides and three angles. The three sides of a triangle can have different lengths, and the angles can vary in size, but the sum of the angles in any triangle is always  <m>180^\circ</m>.    
                </p>

                <p>
                    Types of Triangles
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Equilateral Triangle : All three sides and angles are equal.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                            Isosceles Triangle : Two sides are equal in length, and two angles are equal. 
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Right Triangle : One angle is exactly <m>90^\circ</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Acute Triangle : All angles are less than <m>90^\circ</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Scalene Triangle : All three sides and angles are different.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Obtuse Triangle : One angle is greater than <m>90^\circ</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                
            </statement>
        </definition>
